While there has been some expermints in letting people in to venues, like for the snooker final in Shelfield. These expermints have not been large enough or analysed, to change the Govement's position on opening up the grounds for a large number of fans (25000) into a Premier League match before 24th May, so I've back 100% No.

With the latest four-step lockdown restrictions timetable from 23rd February: -Assumption - Premier league matches will not fall under the 'Outdoor Sports facilities/grassroots sporting games' easing scheduled for 29th March earliest -Assumption - Access and Egress from the stadiums will be more difficult to handle than socially distancing fans in their seating -Allowing for distancing of 1.5-2M between fans could require 3-4 seats empty between fans on each row, and 2 empty rows between seated rows [ https://parametricmonkey.com/2017/10/23/seating-bowl/ ] -Only 3 or 4 UK stadiums have capacity of approx 75000 or more and still would struggle to seat 25000 fans under current social contact limitations -Current social contact limitations will not be lifted before 21st June, under the recent revisions

We will need to see several consecutive weeks of dramatic reductions in cases and hospitalisations before fans are allowed to return to large sporting events. Social distancing measures look likely to be implemented when fans do return, leading to reduced capacity. It appears unlikely enough will change before the end of the 2020/21 season for attendances of 25,000 to be made possible. 2% possibility provided for 16 March - 23 May due to possibility of government adopting an aggressive reopening strategy in March and April as the vaccine rollout takes effect and pressure from the Treasury grows.
Adjusting forecast by 3% based on latest projections for general population over 18 vaccination plans (current UK Gov forecast September 2021).

Under UK law currently fans are restricted depending on the tier they fall into. This will not allow 25,000 until COVID law changes. Do not see this happening before this season is over. But there is a lot of time and with vaccine role out and summer coming to hopefully help with the spread there is still a small chance, but I see the EPL taking it slow and not jumping to much past the 4,000 mark.

Covid vaccinations will need to be in the large majority of the population before this can happen. Also we don't yet know the ecological validity of the vaccine on a mass scale, only its efficacy in test trials. We need the vaccine to have been administered to people in the age brackets of 30-50. Average age of a premier league football fan is 41. That is currently estimated by Omni calc to be July at the earliest with 1m vaccines a week. Highly unlikely this will be allowed. I bloody hope it will be allowed again one day!

25,000 is a large number of fans, and no stadium in the Premier League could maintain a number of fans that large with social distancing. The government has promised we will be "back to normal" by Easter, but such promises are worth little. Also, large events will be the last thing to return to normal. If the vaccine rollout goes particularly well, or if cases really drop off, we may have 25,000 fans back in the stadium as normal. However, it's more likely they will use the FA Cup as the big "back to stadiums" event, and start larger attendances next season.

1) Premier League calendar: The season will end very shortly after full restrictions are lifted (end of March). The start of April is game week 30 out of 38. Will the premier league see it worth allowing fans back in large capacity for 8 game weeks? I think not.

Manchester United have the largest capacity ground in the country and 25,000 equates to roughly 1/3 capacity. So essentially the question boils down to when will the Premier League allow 1/3 capacity at games. Current guidance is for 1000-2000 and is likely to remain the status quo until at least the spring. The 2021/22 season would likely begin before October 2020 though. Is it possible that 25,000 could be allowed back into grounds for this point. In Japan's J-League there have already been sporting events with ~50% capacity despite Covid still being an outstanding issue. I think it is very possible although not likely given transport issues getting to grounds. I assign a 25% probability to this scenario. The next two windows are narrower, and I see it as less likely that restrictions would be eased during winter months should Covid remain an issue. I see only a relatively small chance that no game will see a 25,000 attendance before May 2021 as ultimately money talks and there will be severe pressure to at least trial such a scenario. Therefore I assign a relatively low 5% to the final scenario.

The current news cycle appears to put "a return to normalcy" towards Easter/early April for the UK. News sites tend to paint things more optimistically than it will end up turning out. There is currently a lot of buzz around vaccine schedules so I will assign a base belief with the majority after May 24 (to account for distribution delays) and update in 2 weeks. There is always the possibility of an early "vaccine stunt" where they fill a stadium full of vaccinated people for a game to increase population compliance to build morale.
The focus on Old Trafford has to be put to the side now that varying capacities by localised area are being allowed.

Increased likelihood of march to may option because of imminent availability of vaccines but not by much as theres still plenty of questions regarding the logistics of distribution of the vaccines making large scale events doubtful till late spring at the earliest.

The only chance I see before March is some sort of charity event where vaccinated key workers are given tickets. March-May is possible perhaps if citywide testing works and there is a big drop in numbers. However, the problem is there are few stadiums big a enough to get 25k in whilst adhering to social distancing - the only way I see it happening is if people are vaccinated, and given the proposed rollout approach, you are looking at that being some time off.

Current obstacles to overcome with mass testing: - Liverpool Council is still running the pilot scheme for effectiveness. There have been no conclusions drawn yet. Notably, there is no information on the types of people submitting themselves to a test, which obviously influences the positive rates. A football crowd's positive rates could be very different. - Similarly, there is no information on invalid tests and what the process is in the case of an invalid test. - Liverpool's city-wide mass testing capacity, with the 20mins 'pregnancy style' test, is currently 50,000 per day. Football clubs will have a couple of hours before the game to test their crowd - imagine the infrastructure, workforce and expense that entails. - Liverpool Council have so far managed to test ~23,000 with 150 positive cases. It is clear that football clubs would have to test over 25,000 because some will test positive which means (1) they cannot attend the game and (2) their mates they arrived with cannot attend the game.

Manchester United have said about 23,500 fans can be safely accommodated in Old Trafford under the current social distance guidelines. As such, it appears that no Premier League teams stadium is large enough to seat +25,000 under current guidelines.

Rapid testing is being rolled out. PM reckons that they will have city-wide rapid testing available at some point before the spring. Equally, his comments during briefing today were extremely optimistic re:spring situation. Maybe that is empty reassurance, maybe it isn't.

Covid cases are at all-time highs in England right now and they are unlikely to go down much over the winter. While ticket sales mean money the lawsuits and safety issues associated with getting people into the stands prematurely simply isn't worth the risk. It will likely take months for them to phase in enough fans to a single stadium to meet this criteria and that will only begin once cases have gone down from where they are perched right now. Ultimately, I think fans will be allowed back into the stadiums en masse come next season. Before then, it'll be mostly empty seats and authorized personnel only.

We appear to be a long way from having fans in grounds in England - any fans this year seems practically impossible. In addition, Manchester United have recently proposed a COVID-19 capacity of ~23,500. This is by some way the largest club ground in the PL, and whilst Old Trafford is aging and may be less easily converted to appropriate distancing measures, this still represents less than a third of the standard capacity. As such it seems unlikely even the newer, though smaller stadiums are going to manage to get closer to half full (e.g. the other three 60,000 seater stadiums would be 40% capacity). In addition, I imagine significantly smaller volumes of spectators will be allowed in initially, and several weeks of evaluation to determine if attending games results in spikes of cases. At present, COVID cases are going in the wrong direction - opening up football stadiums is far from governments minds. I will re-evaluate in the new year, or when a vaccine is found.

This is subject to local laws but does indicate a potential move to test fan attendance at European football matches. This could well be a precursor to implementation in the premier league so the results of any large scale trials will help inform likely future timelines.

First, we are unlikely to have any vaccine available to the general public before Spring of next year. Even potential vaccines being prepped now are slated to go public in the Summer. Second, once a vaccine is widely available, it is almost impossible to see the Premier League being a top priority for true reopenings. There are not tests available that would be practical for game attendees and the liabilities of allowing thousands of fans into a game that may or may not have been immunized or have the virus is huge. Moreover, fans have already become accustomed to the current state of things and while they will expect the games to return to normal at some point it is unlikely enough will demand we get back to business before the season's end to put any real pressure on the EPL or British government, especially as we are perhaps at the beginning of a second wave even today.

return of fans on a large scale is not likely until a vaccine is generally available. winter months may see more covid cases and no vaccine. possible in the spring given potential for herd immunity/vaccine/treatment development but unlikely that governments will be swift to reopen sporting events that are seen as super spreading events.

As of now, with no vaccine likely before the end of the year, it remains nearly impossible to see a stadium with 25,000 fans in the UK. Even games with the Premier Leagues' most popular teams, for example, Liverpool, Chelsea, Tottenham, 25,000 would still be nearly at 50% capacity. The long hold out, and a possible source of optimism, is Old Trafford. With a capacity of nearly 75,000 attendance of 25,000 would be only 33%, which still seems high. Additionally, with the UK seeing increases in numbers and shelving plans for limited fan attendance in the coming weeks, it seems unlikely to see attendance levels anywhere close. The possibility of a vaccine being produced for large scale production in Q1 2021 leaves open a slight chance of larger gatherings in the mid-March to mid-May timeframe. Trial fixtures with 1000 fans have just been cancelled due to increasing numbers of COVID cases. Social distancing measures have been increased such as shutting pubs at 10pm and the rule of 6, however case numbers are now exponential with an R rate over 1. It is to be seen whether these measures alone are sufficient and it is possible that cases will continue to rise leading to further lockdown and not less. Also this situation is unlikely to abate over the winter months and a vaccine will most likely not be available on sufficient scale to conduct a nationwide vaccine programme till next year. As a result the probability of at least 25k fans attending a premier league this year are highly remote. A vaccine development this year, the commencement of spring, or a reduction in case numbers could result in the potential for a 25k+ match to be held towards the end of Q1. Although nearing the end of the season clubs generate significant revenue from stadium attendance and there will be immense pressure to accommodate stadium capacities if a change in situation warrants.
